    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor=lightgrey];

    // Define nodes
    PRESSURE_SENSORS [label="Pressure Sensors (x8)"];
    TEMP_SENSORS [label="Temp Sensors (x8)"];
    INSTRUMENTATION_AMPS [label="Instrumentation Amplifiers (x8)"];
    TEMP_LINEARIZATION [label="Temperature Linearization (x8)"];
    MUX [label="16-to-1 Analog Multiplexer"];
    SAMPLE_HOLD [label="Sample & Hold Circuit"];
    ANTI_ALIASING [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter"];
    ADC [label="Analog-to-Digital Converter"];
    DATA_INTERFACE [label="Digital Interface to Computer"];

    // Connect nodes
    PRESSURE_SENSORS -> INSTRUMENTATION_AMPS;
    TEMP_SENSORS -> TEMP_LINEARIZATION;
    INSTRUMENTATION_AMPS -> MUX;
    TEMP_LINEARIZATION -> MUX;
    MUX -> SAMPLE_HOLD;
    SAMPLE_HOLD -> ANTI_ALIASING;
    ANTI_ALIASING -> ADC;
    ADC -> DATA_INTERFACE;
}
```

```Explanations
1. Pressure Sensors (x8): 
   - The strain-gauge sensors are used to measure pressure at eight points on the machine. They have a sensitivity that allows us to measure pressure with an accuracy of at least 1%. A Wheatstone bridge configuration can be employed to convert pressure-induced strain into a voltage signal.

2. Temperature Sensors (x8): 
   - Infrared radiation detectors will measure surface temperature. They have a nonlinear response that requires linearization for accurate readings, and their output can be up to 100 mV.

3. Instrumentation Amplifiers (x8): 
   - These amplify the low-level signals from the pressure sensors, typically 1 mV, to a higher voltage level suitable for the ADC. They need to provide precise gain with low offset and low noise to maintain the accuracy of the pressure readings.

4. Temperature Linearization (x8): 
   - A circuit or series of circuits designed to linearize the response of the temperature sensors. This could be done through analog computation methods or by using specific components that counteract the non-linearity of the sensors.

5. 16-to-1 Analog Multiplexer:
   - This device selects one of the 16 sensor signals (eight temperature and eight pressure) for sequential input to the sample and hold circuit. It is controlled by the ADC or an external control logic to sequentially switch between the channels.

6. Sample & Hold Circuit: 
   - It captures and holds the analog voltage of the selected sensor at a constant level during the ADC conversion process. This ensures that the conversion is made on a stable signal even if the input changes during the ADC's sampling time.

7. Anti-Aliasing Filter: 
   - A low-pass filter that removes frequencies higher than 400 Hz from the sensor signals to prevent aliasing in the ADC. It is important that this filter has a sharp cutoff to effectively remove unwanted frequencies.

8. Analog-to-Digital Converter: 
   - This device converts the analog signals from the sensors into digital values for processing by a computer. It has to have a resolution sufficient to ensure that the 1% accuracy requirement is maintained after digitization.

9. Digital Interface to Computer: 
   - The final stage that communicates with the computer, sending the digital data for further analysis. It can be a standard interface like USB, Ethernet, or a specific industrial protocol, depending on system requirements.
```

